'''Fred L. Banks Jr.''' (born September 1, 1942) is a former [[Mississippi Supreme Court]] justice,<ref name="MS">{{cite web|url=http://courts.ms.gov/news/2001/9.28.01banks.htm|title=Supreme Court Justice Fred L. Banks Jr. announces he is stepping down|publisher=Mississippi Courts|date=September 28, 2001}}</ref> having served on the court from 1991 to 2001.
==Early life, education, and career== Banks grew up in [[Jackson, Mississippi]], the son of F. L. Banks Sr. and Violet Mabery Banks, and graduated from [[Lanier High School (Jackson, Mississippi)|Lanier High School]] in 1960.<ref name="MC Law">{{cite web|url=http://judicial.mc.edu/judge_profiles.php#banks|title=Profiles of Former Justices and Judges: Fred L. Banks Jr.|publisher= Mississippi College Judicial Data Project|date=December 15, 2000}}</ref> He received a [[B.B.A.]] from [[Howard University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], followed by a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from the [[Howard University School of Law]], in 1968,<ref>Turry Flucker, Phoenix Savage, ''African Americans of Jackson'' (2008), p. 45.</ref><ref name="MS"/> where he graduated ''cum laude'', second in his class.<ref name="MS"/><ref name="MC Law"/> Banks "chose to enter the law to help African Americans achieve equality", being one of only a handful of African American attorneys in the state at the time of his graduation.<ref>Paul Finkelman, ''Encyclopedia of African American History, 1896 to the Present'' (2009), p. 74.</ref> After gaining [[admission to the bar]] in Mississippi, he entered into private practice in Jackson with several other attorneys acting as local counsel for the [[NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund]].<ref name="MC Law"/> He then formed a law firm with several of those attorneys, [[Reuben Anderson]], E.M. Nichols, and [[Melvyn R. Leventhal]].<ref name="MS"/>
==Career== ===Legislative service=== In 1975, Banks was elected to represent [[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds County]] in the [[Mississippi House of Representatives]]. He was twice re-elected.<ref name="MS"/> During his time in the House, Banks chaired the House Ethics Committee, the House Judiciary Committee, and the Legislative Black Caucus.<ref name="MBJ">{{cite web|url=http://msbusiness.com/2013/05/banks-wins-award/|title=Fred Banks wins Inns of Court award|publisher=''[[Mississippi Business Journal]]''|date=May 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name="MS"/> Banks, along with Representatives [[Horace L. Buckley]] and [[Douglas L. Anderson]], also from Jackson, fought to preserve records from the pro-segregation [[Mississippi State Sovereignty Commission]], in opposition to a bill which would authorize the destruction of these records.<ref>Yasuhiro Katagiri, ''The Mississippi State Sovereignty Commission: Civil Rights and States' Rights'' (2007), p. 228.</ref> Also during this period, on September 24, 1979, President [[Jimmy Carter]] announced his appointment of Banks as one of nine members of the National Advisory Council on the Education of Disadvantaged Children.<ref>''Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States, Jimmy Carter, 1979'' (1980), p. 1727.</ref>
===Judicial service=== During this time, Reuben Anderson had been appointed to a seat as a Circuit Judge for the 7th Circuit District, encompassing Hinds County and [[Yazoo County, Mississippi|Yazoo]]. Banks served in the legislature until February 1985, when Anderson was Governor [[William Allain]], having elevated Reuben Anderson to the Mississippi Supreme Court, appointed Banks to Anderson's seat on the 7th Circuit District.<ref name="MS"/> Banks was twice re-elected without opposition.<ref name="MC Law"/> In January 1991, following Anderson's resignation from the Mississippi Supreme Court, Governor [[Ray Mabus]] appointed Banks to fill the remainder of Anderson's term. Banks was elected to serve the remainder of that term in November 1991 and re-elected to a full term in November 1996.<ref name="MC Law"/><ref name="MS"/>
In 1993, Banks was mentioned as a potential nominee to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]], during the administration of President [[Bill Clinton]], as there were no African American judges on the Fifth Circuit.<ref>"Clinton and the Federal Courts", ''[[Black Enterprise]]'' (April 1993), p. 29.</ref> Clinton ultimately appointed Louisiana state court judge [[Carl E. Stewart]] as the first African American judge on the Fifth Circuit.
Banks retired from the court in 2001, and thereafter became a senior partner at the law firm of Phelps Dunbar.<ref name="MBJ"/>
