{{Other uses|Map (disambiguation)}}
In [[mathematics]], the term '''mapping''', sometimes shortened to '''map''', refers to either a [[Function (mathematics)|function]], often with some sort of special structure, or a [[morphism]] in category theory, which generalizes the idea of a function. There are also a few, less common uses in logic and graph theory.
==Maps as functions== {{Main article|Function (mathematics)}}
In many branches of mathematics, the term '''map''' is used to mean a [[Function (mathematics)|function]], sometimes with a specific property of particular importance to that branch. For instance, a "map" is a ''[[continuous function]]'' in [[topology]], a ''[[Linear map|linear transformation]]'' in [[linear algebra]], etc.
Some authors, such as [[Serge Lang]],<ref>{{citation|first=Serge|last=Lang|title=Linear Algebra|edition=2nd|year=1971|page=83|publisher=Addison-Wesley}}</ref> use "function" only to refer to maps in which the [[codomain]] is a set of numbers (i.e. a subset of the [[Field (mathematics)|field]]s '''R''' or '''C''') and the term ''mapping'' for more general functions.
Sets of maps of special kinds are the subjects of many important theories: see for instance [[Lie group]], [[mapping class group]], [[permutation group]].<!-- many more to add here-->
In the theory of [[dynamical system]]s, a map denotes an [[Discrete-time dynamical system|evolution function]] used to create [[Dynamical system#Maps|discrete dynamical systems]]. See also [[Poincaré map]].
A ''partial map'' is a ''[[partial function]]'', and a ''total map'' is a ''[[total function]]''. Related terms like ''[[Domain (mathematics)|domain]]'', ''[[codomain]]'', ''[[Injective function|injective]]'', ''[[Continuous function|continuous]]'', etc. can be applied equally to maps and functions, with the same meaning. All these usages can be applied to "maps" as general functions or as functions with special properties.
==Maps as morphisms== {{Main article|Morphism}}
In [[category theory]], "map" is often used as a synonym for [[morphism]] or arrow, thus for something more general than a function.<ref>{{citation|title=An Introduction to Category Theory|first=H.|last=Simmons|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2011|isbn=9781139503327|page=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VOCQUC_uiWgC&pg=PA2}}</ref> For example, morphisms <math>f\, X\to Y</math>, in a [[Concrete category| concrete category]], in other words morphisms that can be viewed as functions, carry with them the information of both its domain (the source <math>X</math> of the morphism), but also its co-domain (the target <math>Y</math>). In the widely used definition of function <math>f:X\to Y</math>, this is a subset of <math>X\times Y</math> consisting of all the pairs <math>(x,f(x))</math> for <math>x\in X</math>. In this sense, the function doesn't capture the information of which set <math>Y</math> is used as the co-domain. Only the range <math>f(X)</math> is determined by the function.
==Other uses== ===In logic=== In [[formal logic]], the term '''map''' is sometimes used for a ''[[functional predicate]]'', whereas a function is a [[model (logic)|model]] of such a [[Predicate (logic)|predicate]] in [[set theory]].
===In graph theory=== [[File:Dodecahedron schlegel diagram.png|thumb|An example of a map in [[graph theory]]]]
In [[graph theory]], a '''map''' is a drawing of a [[Graph (discrete mathematics)|graph]] on a surface without overlapping edges (an [[Graph embedding|embedding]]). If the surface is a [[Plane (geometry)|plane]] then a map is a [[planar graph]], similar to a [[political map]].<ref>{{citation|first1=Jonathan|last1=Gross|first2=Jay|last2=Yellen|title=Graph Theory and its applications|year=1998|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=0-8493-3982-0|page=294}}</ref>
===In computer science=== In the communities surrounding [[programming language]]s that treat functions as [[first-class citizen]]s, a [[Map (higher-order function)|map]] often refers to the [[Binary function|binary]] [[higher-order function]] that takes a function ''f'' and a [[List (abstract data type)|list]] {{nowrap|[''v''<sub>0</sub>, ''v''<sub>1</sub>, ..., ''v''<sub>''n''</sub>]}} as [[Argument of a function|arguments]] and returns {{nowrap|[''f''(''v''<sub>0</sub>), ''f''(''v''<sub>1</sub>), ..., ''f''(''v''<sub>''n''</sub>)]}}, where {{nowrap|''n'' ≥ 0}}.
==See also== {{Div col|colwidth=20em}} * [[Bijection, injection and surjection]] * [[Category theory]] * [[Correspondence (mathematics)]] * [[Homeomorphism]] * [[Homomorphism]] * [[List of chaotic maps]] * [[Mapping class group]] * [[Morphism]] * [[Projection (mathematics)]] * [[Regular map (algebraic geometry)]] * [[Regular map (graph theory)]] * [[Topology]] {{div col end}}
